{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510460"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:29:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:29:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11563"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11563"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.53,0.02,0.09,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4192"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115424"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4192"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97427"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"2335"},{"type":"tags","id":"4365"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42628"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48802"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115424"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of severe nausea and vomiting. She is 14 weeks pregnant, G2P1, and has a history of hyperemesis in her previous pregnancy. She has had eight episodes of vomiting daily for the past two days and has had very little oral intake today. She developed nausea and vomiting early in this pregnancy; however, her symptoms have steadily worsened to the extent that she is having difficulty sleeping, working, and maintaining normal oral intake. She has no significant medical history other than her previous hyperemesis gravidarum. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 105/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Her capillary refill time is three seconds, and her mouth appears dry. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. Investigations reveal a blood glucose level of 5.1 mmol/L (3.3-5.5) and urine ketones of 0.4 mmol/L (\u0026lt;0.6). Other investigations are still pending. Intravenous rehydration has been commenced.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acupressure at the P6 point","Intravenous thiamine supplementation","Intravenous hydrocortisone","Oral pyridoxine","Intramuscular promethazine and intravenous ondansetron"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe hyperemesis gravidarum, characterised by persistent nausea and vomiting in pregnancy leading to dehydration and electrolyte imbalances. The most appropriate initial management in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eintramuscular promethazine and intravenous ondansetron\u003C/strong\u003E. These antiemetics provide rapid symptomatic relief, which is crucial before addressing fluid and electrolyte imbalances. The combination of these two medications with different mechanisms of action often provides better control of symptoms than either agent alone. Regarding safety:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPromethazine is category C in pregnancy \u2013 when given in high doses during late pregnancy, there is potentially an increased risk of prolonged neurological disturbances in the infant. It is not known to be teratogenic\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOndansetron is category B1 in pregnancy \u2013 this means there is no clear increased risk of teratogenicity or other harmful effects observed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotential risks of these therapies should be balanced against the risks of hyperemesis gravidarum, which can be significant, including: dehydration, malnutrition, weight loss, adverse pregnancy outcomes including miscarriage and growth restriction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcupressure at the P6 point\u003C/strong\u003E can be effective for mild nausea in pregnancy and carries no risk of harm. However, given the severity of this patient\u0027s symptoms, it would be insufficient as the primary intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous thiamine supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is important in the management of hyperemesis gravidarum to prevent Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy, particularly in patients with prolonged vomiting and poor nutritional intake. However, it does not address the immediate symptom control needed in this case and would typically be given alongside antiemetic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in severe or refractory cases of hyperemesis gravidarum. However, it is not the first-line treatment and should only be considered after antiemetic therapy has been tried. There are also concerns about potential fetal risks, although recent studies suggest these may be minimal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral pyridoxine\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as vitamin B6, can be effective for mild nausea in pregnancy, especially when combined with doxylamine. However, it has limited effect on vomiting and would be insufficient for this patient\u0027s severe symptoms. It may be more useful as a preventive measure in subsequent pregnancies for women with a history of hyperemesis gravidarum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antiemetic therapy is first-line medication for treatment of severe nausea and vomiting in pregnancy that has resulted in dehydration.","Intravenous fluid administration and electrolyte replacement is often necessary in patients presenting with severe hyperemesis gravidarum.","Doxylamine, pyridoxine (vitamin B6) and acupressure can be effective for mild nausea and vomiting in pregnancy."],"references":["O\u0027Donnell A, McParlin C, Robson SC, Beyer F, Moloney E, Bryant A, et al. Treatments for hyperemesis gravidarum and nausea and vomiting in pregnancy: a systematic review and economic assessment. Health technology assessment (Winchester, England). 2016;20(74):1\u2013268. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27731292","Lowe SA, Bowyer L, Beech A, Robinson H, Armstrong G, Marnoch C, Grzeskowiak L. Guideline for the Management of nausea and vomiting in pregnancy and hyperemesis gravidarum. In: Society of Obstetric Medicine of Australia and New Zealand [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.somanz.org/content/uploads/2020/07/NVP-GUIDELINE-1.2.20-1.pdf","Wong ZYW, Ou KQ, Prasad A, Say WX, Nalliah  S. Management of hyperemesis gravidarum [Internet]. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2023. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2022/october/guidelines-for-the-management-of-hyperemesis-gravi","Lowe S, Bowyer L, Beech A, Robinson H, Armstrong G, Marnoch C, et al. GUIDELINE FOR THE MANAGEMENT OF NAUSEA AND VOMITING IN PREGNANCY AND HYPEREMESIS GRAVIDARUM [Internet]. 2019. Available from: https://www.somanz.org/content/uploads/2020/07/NVP-GUIDELINE-1.2.20-1.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97427"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11563"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97427"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T17:02:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T17:03:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4192"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115424"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medi